00:40:11.049 --> 00:40:15.420
&gt;Sanjayan: Great question. So how are salamanders
and I'd say amphibians and frogs doing?

00:40:15.420 --> 00:40:21.289
So they're not doing very well because most
things like frogs and amphibians and toads

00:40:21.289 --> 00:40:25.859
need both land and water to survive. So you
can't just protect land, you also have to

00:40:25.859 --> 00:40:30.700
protect water. And water pollution is a really
big, big problem with pesticides and things

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:31.700
like that.

00:40:31.700 --> 00:40:36.930
So most of them aren't doing that well. There
are some that are doing some, that are doing

00:40:36.930 --> 00:40:37.930
pretty well.

00:40:37.930 --> 00:40:42.520
In California you have really great salamander
called the tiger salamander. It's a really

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:47.690
big salamander and he's got spots and he kinda
looks like a tiger. If you pick him up, which

00:40:47.690 --> 00:40:51.781
you shouldn't really do, but if you do, he'll
croak at you. He'll go, "Raa" like that, like

00:40:51.781 --> 00:40:53.450
a little tiger. It's pretty cool.

00:40:53.450 --> 00:40:57.569
And that salamander's actually doing really
well because, well they're doing well in some

00:40:57.569 --> 00:41:02.960
places because we're working with farmers
and land owners to really protect the grassland

00:41:02.960 --> 00:41:07.650
for that salamander needs to live in. So the
Nature Conservancy and other local land trusts

00:41:07.650 --> 00:41:11.579
are working all over California to protect
that salamander, the tiger salamander.

00:41:11.579 --> 00:41:12.579
