00:41:12.579 --> 00:41:16.089
&gt;&gt;male in audience #2: You talked about the
fish bank in Solomon Islands --

00:41:16.089 --> 00:41:17.089
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: Yeah.

00:41:17.089 --> 00:41:19.339
&gt;&gt;male in audience #2: you explained how--how
the locals there prefer to think of it as

00:41:19.339 --> 00:41:23.690
a fish bank as opposed to conserva--conservancy.
It seems to me that argument would be true

00:41:23.690 --> 00:41:28.039
pretty much anywhere in the developed world
as well. Have you had success in trying to

00:41:28.039 --> 00:41:30.650
replicate that for cod or various other fishes?

00:41:30.650 --> 00:41:35.420
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: We've had tremendous success with
our argument of using banks as a catch phrase

00:41:35.420 --> 00:41:40.160
to--to talk about a collective resource the
community can draw on in times of trouble.

00:41:40.160 --> 00:41:45.219
So not only do we have fish banks we also
now have grass banks; That are grassland areas

00:41:45.219 --> 00:41:49.479
that the community agrees to set aside for
wildlife like in Northern Kenya we're doing

00:41:49.479 --> 00:41:54.289
enormous projects there; where we're setting
aside huge grass banks as well as in the United

00:41:54.289 --> 00:41:58.712
States, California, Arizona, places like that,
where the community says, "We've gonna leave

00:41:58.712 --> 00:42:03.349
this for-for wildlife, but in times of drought
when everyone's rushing to sell their cattle

00:42:03.349 --> 00:42:07.729
and so all the cattle prices deflate, we can
go in there and graze it in that, in that

00:42:07.729 --> 00:42:08.729
time."

00:42:08.729 --> 00:42:12.039
And it's a, it's a very attractive argument
to poor communities who constantly go through

00:42:12.039 --> 00:42:17.619
boom and bust cycles of have and then everyone
then no rain then all cattle are dying then

00:42:17.619 --> 00:42:19.930
everyone's selling at the same time.

00:42:19.930 --> 00:42:24.900
With fish banks we have in lots of different
kinds of things. One really cool thing we're

00:42:24.900 --> 00:42:31.270
doing right here off the coast of--of California,
just south of here, is basically buying trawler

00:42:31.270 --> 00:42:36.630
permits and taking a lot of the trawlers that
are having the biggest harm on certain areas

00:42:36.630 --> 00:42:37.630
out of business.

00:42:37.630 --> 00:42:42.299
So we own the license, the Nature Conservancy
does, but then we put them back out and just

00:42:42.299 --> 00:42:47.549
give it to them under conditions where they
can fish more sustainably using line methods

00:42:47.549 --> 00:42:51.200
for example. And then keeping them out of
the most sensitive areas as well.

00:42:51.200 --> 00:42:55.729
So there's a lot of really clever stuff going
on where we're trying to engage with economic

00:42:55.729 --> 00:43:02.210
interests to not put them out of business,
but to use our might and our dollars to steer

00:43:02.210 --> 00:43:03.799
in a different direction.

