00:43:32.599 --> 00:43:38.380
of food we had because we didn't pack like
that. We just thought about, you think about

00:43:38.380 --> 00:43:44.489
it in cups like so we each would have one
cup of this thing that looks like porridge

00:43:44.489 --> 00:43:49.180
and then like one can of like tomato which
we'd put on top and maybe a can of sardines

00:43:49.180 --> 00:43:51.190
that we'd throw on top of that, and eat that
for dinner.

00:43:51.190 --> 00:43:56.140
So we didn't think of it in pounds. I will
tell you for water, which is the real issue,

00:43:56.140 --> 00:44:00.479
'cause you can last without food for very
long. Water, we were each using about seven

00:44:00.479 --> 00:44:05.280
liters of water a day. That's seven bottles,
big bottles of water every day. That's for

00:44:05.280 --> 00:44:11.619
everything. That's for showering quickly;
that's for brushing my teeth; that's for drinking;

00:44:11.619 --> 00:44:12.809
and that's for cooking.

00:44:12.809 --> 00:44:19.019
And just to give you an idea, that's how much
we used every day for 20 days. If you, if

00:44:19.019 --> 00:44:22.599
you are in West Africa you would use about
35 liters of water a day.

00:44:22.599 --> 00:44:26.240
You know much Americans use, here, you know
how much I use in America?

00:44:26.240 --> 00:44:27.319
&gt;&gt;Alan Eustace: Wanna make a guess?

00:44:27.319 --> 00:44:29.920
&gt;&gt;Anika: I don't know.

00:44:29.920 --> 00:44:35.420
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: Seven hundred liters of water
a day; seven hundred. So that means we're

00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:37.190
probably wasting a lot of it, don't you think?

00:44:37.190 --> 00:44:38.190
[pause]

00:44:38.190 --> 00:44:41.100
&gt;&gt;Alan Eustace: Any other questions?

00:44:41.100 --> 00:44:42.100
Yeah, here.

00:44:42.100 --> 00:44:47.480
&gt;&gt;male in audience #3: I won't tell you how
old I am.

00:44:47.480 --> 00:44:48.480
[laughter]

00:44:48.480 --> 00:44:52.299
So this takes lots of money. How does the
Nature Conservancy fund these projects?

00:44:52.299 --> 00:44:53.840
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: It's a great question.

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:58.979
So the Nature Conservancy gets most of its
money from individual donors. We have about

00:44:58.979 --> 00:45:04.059
a million members around the world and they
send in from 50 dollar memberships to much,

00:45:04.059 --> 00:45:05.479
much bigger than that.

00:45:05.479 --> 00:45:11.769
We also get a chunk of money from foundations
that support it, many of them in the Bay Area;

00:45:11.769 --> 00:45:15.859
Moore foundation, Hewlett-Packard all those
foundations give the Conservancy money to

00:45:15.859 --> 00:45:16.859
do it.

00:45:16.859 --> 00:45:20.229
And then there's a small amount of money that
we use where we leverage government money

00:45:20.229 --> 00:45:22.099
to get something big done.

00:45:22.099 --> 00:45:27.739
So that's how the Conservancy, it raises money
the old-fashioned way through members like

00:45:27.739 --> 00:45:29.019
you and like others like you.

00:45:29.019 --> 00:45:30.019
[pause]

00:45:30.019 --> 00:45:32.140
&gt;&gt;male in audience #4: That wasn't a real
egg was it?

00:45:32.140 --> 00:45:33.140
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: Huh?

00:45:33.140 --> 00:45:35.390
&gt;&gt;male in audience #4: That thing you were
shaking was not a real egg?

00:45:35.390 --> 00:45:39.229
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: It is a real egg. What do you
think I'm doing like faking these kids out?

00:45:39.229 --> 00:45:40.229
[laughter]

00:45:40.229 --> 00:45:41.229
[pause]

00:45:41.229 --> 00:45:43.599
&gt;&gt;male in audience #4: Does it really survive?

00:45:43.599 --> 00:45:46.400
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: Here pass it, no, no, no. It's
look.

00:45:46.400 --> 00:45:47.400
[laughter]

00:45:47.400 --> 00:45:49.930
I've eaten what's inside it. Okay.

00:45:49.930 --> 00:45:54.280
Let's go show, let's go show him 'cause I
don't think you believe it.

00:45:54.280 --> 00:45:55.749
&gt;&gt;male in audience #4: Like you, you were
shaking it so much --

00:45:55.749 --> 00:45:56.749
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: Oh.

00:45:56.749 --> 00:45:57.749
&gt;&gt;male in audience #4: I was like --

00:45:57.749 --> 00:46:02.460
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: Yeah, that ostrich, no, that ostrich,
no, it was a, a unfertilized egg from an ostrich

00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:04.059
that I actually personally knew.

00:46:04.059 --> 00:46:06.769
&gt;&gt;male in audience #4: Oh, okay. [laughs]

00:46:06.769 --> 00:46:07.769
[laughter]

00:46:07.769 --> 00:46:13.219
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: It's actually true. It's one lonely
female that lives on a farm.

00:46:13.219 --> 00:46:14.219
[pause]

00:46:14.219 --> 00:46:16.849
&gt;&gt;male in audience #5: I really appreciated
you drawing a link between conservation and

00:46:16.849 --> 00:46:21.089
health and people living better lives. And
you gave us really great examples of how people

00:46:21.089 --> 00:46:24.339
who live with very little means do that.

00:46:24.339 --> 00:46:26.829
How can we draw that connection in our own
communities and perhaps in our own country

00:46:26.829 --> 00:46:30.329
where people live with great means and I think
don't make that connection?

00:46:30.329 --> 00:46:38.230
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: You know, so here's the way to
do this. I've had a struggle with it and it's

00:46:38.230 --> 00:46:43.989
very hard to talk about conservation to people
who don't think maybe just like us. So you

00:46:43.989 --> 00:46:48.829
have to use whatever the words, whatever language
you can to talk about something that has real

00:46:48.829 --> 00:46:49.940
meaning to their lives.

00:46:49.940 --> 00:46:56.380
Rachel Carson 40 years ago she took on the
pesticide industry and broke them. I mean

00:46:56.380 --> 00:47:03.160
she got DDT banned; one woman. And she did
that by talking to other women living, talking

00:47:03.160 --> 00:47:10.369
directly to women in their kitchens back in
the 60's; talking to them about health and

00:47:10.369 --> 00:47:14.940
safety for their kids. So she said, "Look
if the songbirds aren't singing out there

00:47:14.940 --> 00:47:19.839
in the woods do you really want your kids
playing out there? If the songbirds are dying,

00:47:19.839 --> 00:47:21.910
do you really want your kids out on the grass
lawn?"

00:47:21.910 --> 00:47:28.170
I--I think that the problem with conservation
right now, this is my generation that we did

00:47:28.170 --> 00:47:32.859
this, we started talking about biodiversity
and biodiversity became this all encompassing

00:47:32.859 --> 00:47:33.859
thing.

00:47:33.859 --> 00:47:38.579
And we said, "You go into a forest, you go
into coral reef, and the diversity of life

00:47:38.579 --> 00:47:43.359
blows us away." And because it blows us away
and listen, I, make no apology I live in Montana.

00:47:43.359 --> 00:47:46.700
I live in Montana because I wanna live in
a place where there's a big animal that could

00:47:46.700 --> 00:47:51.720
potentially kill me when I go for a walk.
I like that sort of stuff. But I'm a pretty

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:54.869
rare individual when it comes to the grand
scheme of things.

00:47:54.869 --> 00:47:59.733
So the truth of the matter is, this notion
that nature's out there and it should be protected

00:47:59.733 --> 00:48:06.059
in all its glory almost like a cathedral,
I think is a bit false. We have thought so

00:48:06.059 --> 00:48:10.989
much about, what we need to do more is think
about how to integrate people in it; talking

00:48:10.989 --> 00:48:14.779
about not nature from people but nature for
people.

00:48:14.779 --> 00:48:17.920
And you can do it in simple ways: you can
talk about energy efficiencies in the Bay

00:48:17.920 --> 00:48:24.630
Area. That is definitely within reach of everyone
here. Early adopters, right? Or you talk about

00:48:24.630 --> 00:48:29.459
how water goes into the Bay; you talk about
food you eat, where you're getting that food

00:48:29.459 --> 00:48:31.480
from. It does make a difference.

00:48:31.480 --> 00:48:32.480
[pause]

00:48:32.480 --> 00:48:34.779
&gt;&gt;Alan Eustace: One more question maybe before
 --

00:48:34.779 --> 00:48:35.990
&gt;&gt;Sanjayan: Right next to you.

00:48:35.990 --> 00:48:40.690
&gt;&gt;male in audience #6: What's the biggest
problem you run into when you're tryin' to

00:48:40.690 --> 00:48:43.359
create like fish banks and other banks?

00:48:43.359 --> 00:48:49.420
&gt;Sanjayan: There're are two problems. One
is the--the issue that the gentleman talked

00:48:49.420 --> 00:48:53.239
about a little bit before, conservation takes
money.

00:48:53.239 --> 00:48:57.700
And when we talk about fish banks we're talkin'
about them in the Solomon Islands, well guess

00:48:57.700 --> 00:49:01.880
what most of our donors don't live there;
they live here.

00:49:01.880 --> 00:49:04.859
People like to give to things that are in
their own backyard. It's hard to get them

00:49:04.859 --> 00:49:10.890
to make that leap to some place very, very
far away. So you are really resource constrained

00:49:10.890 --> 00:49:15.380
when you do conservation in these far away
places. That's the na--nature of the beast.

00:49:15.380 --> 00:49:17.549
So that's one issue.

00:49:17.549 --> 00:49:23.029
The second issue is gaining people's trust.
So that's really hard. You could, you should

00:49:23.029 --> 00:49:27.459
never promise something to people that you
don't really wanna stand behind. It doesn't

00:49:27.459 --> 00:49:32.500
mean you can't make a mistake, but you can't
mislead them in any way at all. You have to

00:49:32.500 --> 00:49:36.619
be completely transparent. If the numbers
don't add up and you're just asking them to

00:49:36.619 --> 00:49:41.069
say, "Look take a jump with me on this," then
tell 'em that. But you can't fake it, it'll

00:49:41.069 --> 00:49:44.549
catch up with you. It'll catch up with you
so fast and it'll all blow up. And I've seen

00:49:44.549 --> 00:49:47.099
it happen in conservation over and over and
over again.

00:49:47.099 --> 00:49:51.980
So you have to be really honest and transparent
when you talk to local communities. You never

00:49:51.980 --> 00:49:54.839
talk down to people just because they speak
a different language.

00:49:54.839 --> 00:50:00.089
Those aboriginal people they knew more about
the environment than you could find out on

00:50:00.089 --> 00:50:05.059
the Internet today. They had this intimate
understanding of it and--and appreciated what

00:50:05.059 --> 00:50:09.569
they're bringing to the table is as valuable
as what you're bringing to the table, it's

00:50:09.569 --> 00:50:10.569
just different scale.

00:50:10.569 --> 00:50:14.359
And then be honest and open when you're having
discussions with them. That's the hardest

00:50:14.359 --> 00:50:15.549
challenge.

00:50:15.549 --> 00:50:16.549
Thank you guys so much.

00:50:16.549 --> 00:50:18.749
[applause]

